				<h1 style="font-size:30px; line-height:40px; text-shadow:0px 0px 5px #000">Choose Orange</h1>
				<div class="horizontaldots"></div>
				<p><strong>Goal: </strong>Have students participate in the &ldquo;Choose Orange&rdquo; campaign to encourage positive, supportive behavior.</p>
				<div class="infobox" style="text-align:center;"> <strong>Materials:</strong> <br />
					<ul>

						<li>Posters</li>
						<li>Orange marker and one other colored marker </li>
					</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div class="contentrow row-whiteblue">
			<div class="singlecolumn">
				<h3 style="text-align:center">Activity</h3>
				<h3><img src="/bullying/getinvolved/images/choose-orange-band.png" width="160" height="397" align="right" hspace="10" vspace="10"/></h3>
				<ol>
					<li>Have students brainstorm adjectives that describe people who are involved in a bullying situation &ndash; the target, the person bullying, and the bystander. Suggestions included: bullied, hurt, alone, lost, sad, scared, desperate, hopeless, silent, defeated.</li>
					<li>Then have students brainstorm verbs that describe what they would like to see happen at their school to end bullying. Suggestions include: acknowledge, act, heal, change, believe, empower, embrace, mentor, unite, peace. If possible, write these words in orange.</li>
					<li>Tell students that they have the power to make either of these lists happen &ndash; they control whether or not bullying happens at their school. Ask who would like to choose the positive, orange group of words. </li>
					<li>As each student raises their hand, give them either an  orange silicone band&mdash;will need to purchase&mdash;or create an orange paper band, similar to those used in <a href="/bullying/wewillgen/classroom-activities/project-connect.asp">Project Connect</a>.
				  <li>Invite students to wear their wristbands as a reminder to CHOOSE ORANGE &ndash; to choose to act in a way that promotes positivity, kindness, and inclusivity at their school. </li>
				</ol>
			</div>
